357]], [[1958\u201359 Scottish League Cup|1958\u201359]]\n\n===Minor===\n\n*'''[[Scottish Football League First Division]], second tier''':<ref name=\"2nd division\">Known as second division prior to 1975</ref>\n**'''Winners (6):''' [[1896\u201397 in Scottish football|1896\u201397]], [[1899\u20131900 in Scottish football|1899\u20131900]], [[1970\u201371_Scottish_Division_Two|1970\u201371]], [[1975\u201376 Scottish First Division|1975\u201376]], [[2001\u201302 Scottish First Division|2001\u201302]], [[2012\u201313 Scottish First Division|2012\u201313]]\n**Runners up (3): [[1901\u201302 in Scottish football|1901\u201302]], [[1991\u201392 in Scottish football|1991\u201392]], [[2008\u201309 Scottish First Division|2008\u201309]]\n*'''[[Scottish Football League Second Division]], third tier:'''\n**'''Winners:''' [[2000\u201301 in Scottish football|2000\u201301]]\n**'''Play-off Winners:''' [[2005\u201306 in Scottish football|2005\u201306]]\n*'''[[Scottish Challenge Cup]]:'''<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Stevie|title=Queen of the South lifted the Challenge Cup for the second time after a penalty shoot-out victory over Partick Thistle|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22043859|website=www.bbc.co.uk/sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=17 November 2014}}</ref>\n**Runners up: [[2012\u201313 Scottish Challenge Cup|2012\u201313]]\n*'''[[Glasgow Cup]]:'''\n**'''Winners:''' 1934\u201335, 1950\u201351, 1952\u201353, 1954\u201355, 1960\u201361, 1980\u201381, 1988\u201389\n**Runners up (11) 1888\u201389, 1900\u201301, 1911\u201312, 1914\u201315, 1917\u201318, 1919\u201320, 1932\u201333, 1936\u201337, 1959\u201360, 1966\u201367, 1968\u201369\n*'''British Cup:'''\n**'''Winners:''' 1921\n*'''[[Glasgow Merchants Charity Cup]]:'''\n**'''Winners (3):''' 1926\u201327, 1934\u201335, 1948\u201349\n*'''[[Summer Cup (Scottish football)|Summer Cup]]:'''\n**'''Winners:''' 1945\n*'''West of Scotland FA Cup:'''\n**'''Winners: ''' 1879\n*'''Glasgow Dental Cup:'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' 1929\n*'''Greenock Charity Cup:'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/greenockcharitycup |title=Greenock Charity Cup 1884\u20131896 |publisher=Scottish-football-historical-archive.com |date= |accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref>\n**'''Winners:''' 1893\n*'''Paisley Charity Cup:'''\n**'''Winners:''' 1936\n*'''Yoker Cup:'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/yokercup |title=Yoker Cup 1880\u20131883 |publisher=Scottish-football-historical-archive.com |date= |accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref>\n**'''Winners:''' 1881, 1882, 1883\n*'''Arr Craib Trophy:'''<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/sfl/2012/07/23/arr-craib-trophy-sean-welsh-steals-the-show-as-partick-thistle-dump-everton-to-lift-cup-86908-23911553/|title = ARR Craib Trophy: Sean Welsh steals the show as Partick Thistle dump Everton to lift cup|date = 23 July 2012|accessdate = 24 July 2012}}</ref>\n**'''Winners:''' 2012\n*'''[[Tennents' Sixes]]:'''<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bathgate|first1=Stuart|title=When winters were warmed by six appeal|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/when-winters-were-warmed-by-six-appeal-1-2734006|website=www.scotsman.com|publisher=The Scotsman|accessdate=17 November 2014}}</ref>\n**'''Winners:''' 1993 (final winners)\n\n==Club records==\n*'''Highest record home attendance:''' 49,838 vs [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], Scottish First Division, 18 February 1922<ref name=\"Rec\">{{cite web | url=http://ptfc.co.uk/club/records | title=Club Records | publisher=Partick Thistle F.C. | work=ptfc.co.uk | accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref>\n*'''Most league appearances:''' [[Alan Rough]], 410<ref name = \"Rec\"/>\n*'''Most league goals in a season:''' Alec Hair, 41, 1926\u201327<ref name = \"Rec\"/>\n*'''Record defeat:''' 0\u201310 v Queen's Park, Scottish Cup, 3 December 1881<ref name = \"Rec\"/>\n*'''Record victory:''' 16\u20130 v Royal Albert, Scottish Cup 1st round, 17 January 1931<ref name = \"Rec\"/>\n*'''Record points total:''' 78, Scottish First Division, 2012\u201313<ref name = \"Rec\"/>\n*'''Record transfer fee paid:''' \u00a385,000 to Celtic for [[Andy Murdoch (footballer, born 1970)|Andy Murdoch]], February 1991<ref name = \"Rec\"/>\n*'''Record transfer fee received:''' \u00a3350,000 from [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] for [[Liam Lindsay]], June 2017 / \u00a3350,000 from [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] for [[Aidan Fitzpatrick]], July 2019\n\n==European record==\n{{main article|Partick Thistle F.C. in European football}}\nThistle have participated in European competition on three different occasions. On the first occasion, they qualified having finished third in the First Division. They progressed to the second round of the Fairs Cup before being eliminated by [[1. FC Brno|Spartak Brno]]. They qualified for the UEFA Cup in 1972\u201373 after winning the League Cup the previous season; Hungarian side [[Budapest Honv\u00e9d FC|Honv\u00e9d]] eliminated them in the first round.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kennedy|first1=Niall|title=Partick Thistle-Club History|url=http://ptfc.co.uk/club/history|website=www.ptfc.co.uk|publisher=Partick Thistle Football Club|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> Their most recent European campaign was the [[UEFA Intertoto Cup 1995|1995 UEFA Intertoto Cup]], when they finished 4th with four points in Group 6.<ref>{{cite web|title=UEFA history \u2013 Partick Thistle|url=http://www.uefa.com/teamsandplayers/teams/club=59863/profile/history/index.html|website=www.uefa.com|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:red; color:yellow;\" scope=\"col\"|Season\n! style=\"background:red; color:yellow;\" scope=\"col\"|Competition\n! style=\"background:red; color:yellow;\" scope=\"col\"|Round\n! style=\"background:red; color:yellow;\" scope=\"col\"|Opponent\n! style=\"background:red; color:yellow;\" scope=\"col\"|Home\n! style=\"background:red; color:yellow;\" scope=\"col\"|Away\n! style=\"background:red; color:yellow;\" scope=\"col\"|Aggregate\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[1963\u201364 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup|1963\u201364]]\n|rowspan=2|[[Inter-Cities Fairs Cup]]\n|First round\n|{{flagicon|NIR}} [[Glentoran F.C.|Glentoran]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\u20130\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\u20131\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\u20131\n|-\n|Second round\n|{{flagicon|Czechoslovakia}} [[FC Zbrojovka Brno|Spartak Brno]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\u20132\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20134\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\u20136\n|-\n|[[1972\u201373 UEFA Cup|1972\u201373]]\n|[[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]\n|First round\n|{{flagicon|HUN}} [[Budapest Honv\u00e9d FC|Budapest Honv\u00e9d]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20133\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20131\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20134\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[1995 UEFA Intertoto Cup|1995\u201396]]\n|rowspan=4|[[UEFA Intertoto Cup]]\n|rowspan=4|Group 6\n|{{flagicon|AUT}} [[LASK Linz]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2013\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\u20132\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2013\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ISL}} [[Knattspyrnudeild Keflav\u00edk|Keflav\u00edk]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\u20131\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2013\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2013\n|-\n|{{flagicon|FRA}} [[FC Metz|Metz]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2013\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20131<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.footballdatabase.eu/football.coupe.metz.partick-thistle.15522.en.html |title=European Football Database |last1=Angulo |first1=Rodrigo |date=14 October 2007 |website=www.footballdatabase.eu |publisher=FootballDatabase.eu |accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2013\n|-\n|{{flagicon|CRO}} [[NK Zagreb]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20132\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2013\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2013\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n;Sources\n*{{cite book| ref = harv | first = Simon | last = Inglis | title = Football Grounds of Britain | year = 1996 | publisher = Collins Willow | isbn = 978-0-00-218426-7 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Partick Thistle FC}}\n* {{official website|http://www.ptfc.co.uk}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/teams/partick-thistle BBC Sport: Partick Thistle]\n* [http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/sport/partick_thistle Evening Times: Partick Thistle]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k9ubw7aiwIo Grasping the Thistle], 2002 [[BBC Scotland]] documentary\n\n{{Partick Thistle F.C.}}\n{{Scottish Professional Football League}}\n{{Scottish Premier League}}\n{{Scottish Football League}}\n{{Glasgow}}\n{{Football in Glasgow}}\n\n[[Category:Partick Thistle F.C.| ]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1876]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:1876 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League teams]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League teams]]\n[[Category:Scottish Cup winners]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League teams]]\n[[Category:Scottish League Cup winners]]\n[[Category:Partick]]\n[[Category:Maryhill]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| current =2019\u201320 Partick Thistle F.C. season\n| clubname = Partick Thistle\n| image = Partick Thistle FC logo.svg\n| image_size = 200px\n| fullname = Partick Thistle Football Club\n| nickname = Thistle, The Jags, The Maryhill Magyars, The Harry Wraggs\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1876}}\n| ground = [[Firhill Stadium]]\n| capacity = {{SPFL-stadiums|partick}}<ref name=\"capacity\">{{cite web |url=http://spfl.co.uk/clubs/partick/ |title=Partick Thistle Football Club|publisher=Scottish Professional Football League |accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref>\n| chrtitle =\n| chairman = Jacqui Low\n| manager = [[Ian McCall (footballer) |Ian McCall]]\n| league = {{Scottish football updater|PartickT}}\n| season = {{Scottish football updater|PartickT2}}\n| position = {{Scottish football updater|PartickT3}}\n| website = http://www.ptfc.co.uk/\n<!-- Home kit -->| pattern_b1 = _ptfc1920h\n| pattern_la1 = _ptfc1920h\n| pattern_ra1 = _ptfc1920h\n| pattern_sh1 = _ptfc1920h\n| pattern_so1 = _ptfc1920h\n| leftarm1 = FF0000\n| body1 = FFEF00\n| rightarm1 = FF0000\n| shorts1 = FF0000\n| socks1 = FF0000\n<!-- Away kit -->| pattern_b2 = _ptfc1920a\n| pattern_la2 = _ptfc1920a\n| pattern_ra2 = _ptfc1920a\n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = _ptfc1920a\n| leftarm2 = FFFFFF\n| body2 = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2 = FFFFFF\n| shorts2 = 000000\n| socks2 = 000000\n}}\n'''Partick Thistle Football Club''' (nicknamed the '''Jags''') are a professional [[association football|football]] club from [[Glasgow]], Scotland. Despite their name, the club are based at [[Firhill Stadium]] in the [[Maryhill]] area of the city, and have not played in [[Partick]] since 1908. The club have been members of the [[Scottish Professional Football League]] (SPFL) since its formation in 2013. Thistle currently compete in the [[Scottish Championship]], the second tier of the SPFL structure, following relegation via play-offs from the [[Scottish Premiership]] in the 2017\u201318 season.  \n\nSince 1936, Thistle have played in their distinctive red-and-yellow jerseys of varying designs, with hoops, stripes and predominantly yellow tops with red trims having been used, although in 2009 a centenary kit was launched in the original navy-blue style to commemorate 100 years at Firhill.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Vassallo|first1=Jean|last2=Paul|title=Partick Thistle Centenary Kits Launched|url=http://www.football-shirts.co.uk/fans/partick-thistle-centenary-kits-launched_5186|website=www.football-shirts.co.uk|publisher=Football Shirts News|accessdate=8 November 2014}}</ref> Since 1908 the club have won the [[Scottish Football League Second Division|Scottish Second Division]] once and the [[Scottish Football League First Division|Scottish First Division]] (second tier, now the [[Scottish Championship]]) six times, most recently in 2013. Thistle have won the [[Scottish Cup]] and the [[Scottish League Cup]] in 1921 and 1971 respectively.\n\nThe club are currently managed by [[Ian McCall (footballer)|Ian McCall]] in his second spell in charge. Under [[Alan Archibald]]'s management, the club achieved promotion to the newly formed Scottish Premiership in 2013, and remained there for five consecutive seasons. During this spell Thistle secured major investment and in 2017 finished in the top six of Scottish football for the first time in over three decades. Key players such as club legend [[Kris Doolan]] broke numerous records and became one of the club\u2019s top goal scorers. Despite relegation in the [[2017\u201318 Scottish Premiership]] season, Archibald remained as Thistle's manager. However, after a poor start to the [[2018\u201319 Scottish Championship]] campaign Archibald's 5 year tenure came to an end. He returned to the club as McCall's assistant in 2019.\n\n==History==\n\n===Formation and early years===\n[[File:Partick Thistle FC League Performance.svg|thumb|300px|right|Chart of yearly table positions of Partick Thistle in the Scottish football league.]] Partick Thistle Football Club was formed in 1876 in the burgh of [[Partick]], which was at that time administratively independent of Glasgow (Partick was not subsumed into Glasgow until 1912). The club's first recorded match (and victory) took place in February against a local junior team, named Valencia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ptearlyyears.net/1870s/1875-76 |title=1875\u201376 \u2013 Partick Thistle history \u2013 The Early Years |publisher=Ptearlyyears.net |date= |accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref> The location of this match, and thereby Thistle's first home ground, was recorded as 'Overnewton Park', which is thought to have been located next to Overnewton Road, just south of [[Kelvingrove Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ptearlyyears.net/grounds1/overnewton |title=Overnewton \u2013 Partick Thistle grounds \u2013 The Early Years |publisher=Ptearlyyears.net |date= |accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref> In 1891, Partick Thistle joined the [[Scottish Football Alliance]], one of several competitions set up immediately after the formation of the [[Scottish Football League]] in 1890. The club won the Second Division championship in 1897 and were elected to the First Division. The following season they were re-elected after finishing in eighth place. In 1900 they were elected back to the top level, having finished as Second Division champions again, but were relegated the following season and then promoted in second place in 1902. This would be the last time Thistle changed their division for almost 70 years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Partick Thistle \u2013 Background|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Scottish_Football_League/Partick_Thistle/Partick_Thistle.htm|website=www.historicalkits.co.uk|publisher=Partick Thistle History Archive|accessdate=8 November 2014}}</ref> Since joining the Scottish professional leagues in 1893, Thistle had been an unpredictable side, spending four years in the First Division and five in the Second, winning promotion three times. It was during the [[1902\u201303 Scottish Division One]] season in which Thistle set their highest finish in the Scottish league structure, finishing 8th in the table with 19 points.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kennedy|first1=Neill|title=Sam Kennedy 1902\u20131910|url=http://ptearlyyears.net/sam-kennedy|website=www.ptearlyyears.net|publisher=Neill Kennedy|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> In the following 33 years, they moved from home to home, using parks at [[Kelvingrove Park|Kelvingrove]], Jordanvale, Muirpark, [[Inchview]] among others. In 1897 they moved to [[Meadowside]], where they played until 1908. After being homeless for over a season, they moved to their present home, [[Firhill Stadium]], in the [[Maryhill]] district of [[Glasgow]]. They played their first home match at Firhill, on 18 September 1909, in a 3\u20131 victory against [[Dumbarton Harp F.C.|Dumbarton Harp]].<ref name=\"Ptfc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://ptfc.co.uk/club/history |title=Club History \u2013 Partick Thistle Football Club |publisher=Ptfc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Cup success and league progress===\nIn 1921 Thistle won the [[Scottish Cup]], beating [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] 1\u20130 in the final.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scottish_cup/1885880.stm |title=Beware the Jags sting |publisher=BBC News |date=21 March 2002 |accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref> Johnny Blair scored the only goal of the game, which was held at [[Celtic Park]].<ref name=\"Ptfc.co.uk\"/> The Jags reached the final again nine years later, facing the same opposition, but Rangers won 2\u20131 in a replay following a 0\u20130 draw in the first match. In 1935 the Jags won both the [[Glasgow Cup]] and the Charity Cup, competitions that were taken seriously at the time.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scottish_cup/1885880.stm |title=BBC SPORT &#124; SCOTTISH CUP &#124; Beware the Jags' sting |publisher=BBC News |date=21 March 2002 |accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nAlthough it was over 30 years before Thistle achieved further cup success they not only maintained their top tier status during this period but finished third in the league in 1947\u201348, 1953\u201354 and 1962\u201363.\n\nOn 23 October 1971 [[Davie McParland]]'s team secured the club's most famous result against [[Jock Stein]]'s Celtic in the [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]] final at [[Hampden Park]], Glasgow. 62,470 fans watched Thistle take a dramatic 4\u20130 lead at half time with goals from Alex Rae, Bobby Lawrie and Jimmy Bone amongst the many emerging talents in the Thistle squad including [[Alan Rough]], [[Alex Forsyth (footballer, born 1952)|Alex Forsyth]] and [[Denis McQuade]]. [[Kenny Dalglish]] pulled a goal back for Celtic, however the final result was never in doubt as Thistle eased to a 4\u20131 victory. Ironically before the match, former [[BBC]] sport broadcaster [[Sam Leitch]] stated that \"In Scotland, it's League Cup final day at Hampden Park, where Celtic meet Partick Thistle, who have no chance.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Philip|first1=Robert|title=The day Hansen and Thistle were a thorn in Celtic's side|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2348822/The-day-Hansen-and-Thistle-were-a-thorn-in-Celtics-side.html|website=www.telegraph.co.uk|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|accessdate=6 November 2014|location=London|date=25 October 2006}}</ref>\n\n===Decline and \"Save the Jags\" campaign===\nThistle's fortunes on the pitch declined during the 1980s. Although the club had experienced difficult times before, having dropped into the second tier of Scottish football twice in the 1970s, they had bounced straight back up on both occasions. The relegation of 1982 led to the club's first sustained period outside the top tier since the late 19th century. Between 1986 and 1989, Thistle were owned by [[Ken Bates]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://partickthistleahistory.wikifoundry.com/page/Ken+Bates+Arrives+1986|title=Chelsea chief in Firhill swoop|author=Jim Blair|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|via=Partick Thistle History Archive|year=1986|accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://partickthistleahistory.wikifoundry.com/page/1987+Ken+Bates+Article|title=Man with a mission|author=Alex Cameron|work=Daily Record|via=Partick Thistle History Archive|year=1987|accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/partick-project-a-bridge-too-far-for-ken-1-516572|title=Partick project a bridge too far for Ken|work=[[The Scotsman]]|date=6 March 2004|accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://partickthistleahistory.wikifoundry.com/page/1989+-+Takeover|title=Thistle all Scottish again|author=Ian Paul|work=[[The Herald (Scotland)|Glasgow Herald]]|via=Partick Thistle History Archive|date=15 April 1989|accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref> chairman of [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], whose intention was to use Thistle as a [[feeder club]] for the English team; however few players moved between the clubs during those years, which were also unsuccessful on the field (they finished 8th in the second tier for five seasons running between [[1985\u201386 Scottish First Division|1985\u201386]] and [[1989\u201390 Scottish First Division|1989\u201390]]).\n\nAlthough this period of exile ended with promotion in 1992, mounting financial problems, including a debt of over \u00a31.5&nbsp;million, threatened to put the club out of existence.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Campsie|first1=Alison|title=Wealthy Jaggies inject \u00a31m to cut Partick Thistle debt|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/wealthy-jaggies-inject-1m-to-cut-partick-thistle-debt-1.821811|website=www.heraldscotland.com|publisher=Newsquest|accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref> In 1998 in particular the club was close to going bankrupt and was only kept afloat by the fan-organised \"Save the Jags\" campaign.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McLean|first1=Euan|title=Partick Thistle captain Alan Archibald: Jags were first club to hit financial skids back in 1998.. we should have been the last|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/partick-thistle-captain-alan-archibald-1120171|website=www.dailyrecord.co.uk|publisher=Trinity Mirror|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> Despite avoiding financial oblivion Thistle were relegated to the third tier of Scottish Football in 1997\u201398 and only narrowly avoided a further relegation the following season, finishing in eighth place.\n\n===Revival under John Lambie===\n[[File:John lambie.jpg|thumbnail|right|John Lambie]]\nIn 1999 [[John Lambie (footballer born 1940)|John Lambie]] commenced his third period as manager of the club and under his stewardship Thistle enjoyed a brief revival, winning back-to-back promotions in 2000\u201301 and 2001\u201302, the second of which earned the club a place in the [[Scottish Premier League]]. SPL guidelines at the time stipulated that clubs would only be eligible for promotion to the league if their stadium had a minimum 10,000 seated capacity. To comply with these guidelines the terraced section at the north end of Firhill was replaced with a 2000-seat stand. Speaking in 2004, Thistle chairman Tom Hughes argued the club did not at the time require a stadium with such a large capacity and building the new stand 'seriously affected [their] competitiveness'.<ref>\"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/3508548.stm Hughes Court Warning to SPL]\". ''BBC.co.uk/sport. ''[[BBC Sport]]. Retrieved 29 July 2013.</ref> Thistle maintained their place in the SPL under Lambie by finishing 10th in 2002\u201303, despite being favourites for relegation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scottish Premier League Archive 2002/2003|url=http://spfl.co.uk/premiership/archive/2002-2003/|website=www.spfl.co.uk/archive/2002-2003|publisher=Scottish Professional Football League|accessdate=6 November 2014|ref=SPFL Archive}}</ref>\n\n===Successive relegations and play-off promotion===\nFollowing Lambie's retirement at the end of the 2002\u201303 season, Thistle struggled. [[Gerry Collins (footballer)|Gerry Collins]] (Lambie's previous assistant) was sacked mid-season and replaced with joint player-managers [[Derek Whyte]] and [[Gerry Britton]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Thistle sack boss Collins|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/3250058.stm|website=www.news.bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC|accessdate=8 November 2014|date=30 November 2003}}</ref> This change was not enough to revive the team, and Thistle were relegated at the end of the 2003\u201304 season after [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness]], having won the First Division title, were permitted to groundshare with [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]. In season 2004\u201305 the team continued to struggle and Whyte and Britton were dismissed mid-season. [[Dick Campbell (footballer)|Dick Campbell]], their successor, was unable to avoid relegation to the Second Division. He did return the club to the First Division the following season, through the newly introduced play-off system, having finished 4th in the league. This brought to a close the club's most unpredictable decade, in footballing terms at least: between 1996 and 2006 Thistle had been promoted three times and relegated four times. They were the first team in Scottish football to be relegated from the top flight through successive subsequent relegations (excluding those caused by league reconstruction).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rogerson|first1=Paul|title=Partick Thistle posts loss after second successive relegation|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/partick-thistle-posts-loss-after-second-successive-relegation-1.44164|website=www.heraldscotland.com|publisher=Herald & Times Group|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Ian McCall's tenure, 2007\u20132011===\n[[File:Ian McCall (football manager).jpg|thumbnail|right|McCall managing Thistle]]\nDespite starting well upon returning to the First Division, Dick Campbell was sacked on 27 March 2007,<ref name=\"Campbell\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/6500067.stm | title=Campbell axed by Partick Thistle | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | work=bbc.co.uk/sport | date=27 March 2007 | accessdate=27 July 2013}}</ref> following a succession of poor results.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/thistle-axe-campbell-as-rising-losses-cause-turmoil-1-692675 | title=Thistle axe Campbell as rising losses cause turmoil | publisher=[[The Scotsman]] | work=scotsman.com | date=27 March 2007 | accessdate=27 July 2013}}</ref> A caretaker management team of [[Jimmy Bone]] and [[Terry Butcher]] saw out the season<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/p/partick_thistle/6511877.stm | title=Butcher takes Partick coach role | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | work=bbc.co.uk/sport | date=30 March 2007 | accessdate=27 July 2013}}</ref> before [[Ian McCall (footballer)|Ian McCall]], a former player, was unveiled as manager. [[2007\u201308 Partick Thistle F.C. season|McCall's first season]] saw Thistle finish 6th in the First Division and embark on a successful [[2007\u201308 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]] campaign, reaching the quarter-finals before being defeated by eventual winners [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] after a 1\u20131 draw at Ibrox, Thistle lost the replay 2\u20130 at Firhill.<ref name=\"Rangers\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/7343165.stm | title=Partick Thistle 0\u20132 Rangers | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | work=bbc.co.uk/sport | date=13 April 2008 | accessdate=9 August 2014 | first=Colin | last=Moffat}}</ref> League form further improved in season 2008\u201309 with Thistle exceeding expectations to finish 2nd in the First Division, behind [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]]. This season saw midfielder [[Gary Harkins]] win the Irn Bru Phenomenal Player of the Year and [[Jonathan Tuffey]] become the club's first full international for several years.\n\nMcCall quit his post as manager in April 2011, citing personal reasons.<ref name=\"McCall\">{{cite web | url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/ian-mccall-quits-as-partick-thistle-manager-1-1587242 | title=Ian McCall quits as Partick Thistle manager | publisher=[[The Scotsman]] | work=scotsman.com | date=15 April 2011 | accessdate=27 July 2013}}</ref> [[Jackie McNamara]] was initially appointed as caretaker manager<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/13095728 | title=Ian McCall quits as Partick Thistle manager | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | work=bbc.co.uk/sport | date=15 April 2011 | accessdate=27 July 2013}}</ref> before being made full-time manager of the club at the end of the 2010\u201311 season.<ref name=\"McNamara\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/13376698 | title=Jackie McNamara is appointed Partick Thistle manager | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | work=bbc.co.uk/sport | date=12 May 2011 | accessdate=27 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Jackie McNamara 2011\u20132013===\nMcNamara and assistant [[Simon Donnelly]] guided Thistle to a sixth-place finish in 2011\u201312 season.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/tables/_/league/sco.2/scottish-division-one?cc=5739# | title=2011/12 Scottish Division One Table / Table | publisher=[[ESPN]] | work=ESPN Soccernet | accessdate=27 May 2012}}</ref> The following season Thistle started well and emerged as promotion candidates, competing with [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline]] and [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]] for a place in the following season's top flight. On 29 January 2013 the club gave permission to [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] to speak to McNamara about becoming their new manager.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2012-2013/january_2013/statement_from_partick_thistle_football_club | title=Statement From Partick Thistle | publisher=Partick Thistle F.C. | work=ptfc.co.uk | date=29 January 2013 | accessdate=30 January 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525000113/http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2012-2013/january_2013/statement_from_partick_thistle_football_club | archivedate=25 May 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The following day McNamara and his assistant [[Simon Donnelly]] resigned,<ref name=\"Change\">{{cite web | url=http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2012-2013/january_2013/change_in_management | title=Change in Management Team | publisher=Partick Thistle F.C. | work=ptfc.co.uk | date=30 January 2013 | accessdate=30 January 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928150015/http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2012-2013/january_2013/change_in_management | archivedate=28 September 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> to become the new management team at United.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21249708 | title=Jackie McNamara named as new Dundee United manager | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | work=bbc.co.uk/sport | date=30 January 2013 | accessdate=30 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dundeeunitedfc.co.uk/index.asp?tm=2&nid=4437&cd=2013 | title=Jackie McNamara Announced As Manager | publisher=[[Dundee United F.C.]] | work=dundeeunitedfc.co.uk | date=30 January 2013 | accessdate=30 January 2013}}</ref> Along with Donnelly, Jackie McNamara brought goalkeeper [[Craig Hinchliffe]], [[Paul Paton]] and [[Chris Erskine]] to [[Tannadice]]. Thistle were second in the league at the time and, because McNamara was under contract, compensation was owed to the club.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/football/compensation-agreed-as-partick-end-dispute-over-mcnamara.21341688 | title=Compensation agreed as Partick end dispute over McNamara | publisher=[[The Herald (Glasgow)]] | work=heraldscotland.com | date=14 June 2013 | accessdate=27 July 2013}}</ref> \n\n===Archibald era (2013\u20132018)===\n[[File:ArchieInterview.png|160px|thumbnail|right|Alan Archibald is interviewed before a match.]]\nOn 30 January 2013, [[Alan Archibald]] was appointed as the club's interim manager, with former Thistle player [[Scott Paterson]] as his assistant.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21266397 | title=Partick Thistle name player-coach Alan Archibald as interim boss | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | work=bbc.co.uk/sport | date=30 January 2013 | accessdate=30 January 2013}}</ref> On 22 March, the duo were given the job on a permanent basis<ref name=\"Confirmed\">{{cite web | url=http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2012-2013/march_2013/alan_archibald_-_confirmed_as_new_partick_thistle_manager | title=Alan Archibald \u2013 Confirmed as New Partick Thistle Manager | publisher=Partick Thistle F.C. | work=ptfc.co.uk | date=22 March 2013 | accessdate=22 March 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130325101339/http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2012-2013/march_2013/alan_archibald_-_confirmed_as_new_partick_thistle_manager | archivedate=25 March 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> signing a one-year rolling contract.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/21905413 | title=Partick Thistle appoint Alan Archibald as manager at Firhill | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | work=bbc.co.uk | date=22 March 2013 | accessdate=22 March 2013}}</ref> The following month on 20 April 2013, the club clinched promotion to the [[Scottish Premiership]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/football/crown-of-thorns.20862606 | title=Partick Thistle celebrate promotion to SPL | publisher=[[The Herald (Glasgow)]] | work=heraldscotland.com | date=21 April 2013 | accessdate=27 July 2013}}</ref> having sealed the [[Scottish Football League First Division|First Division]] championship with a 2\u20130 victory away to [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/football/first/results/3520276/ | title=Thistle are champions | publisher=[[Scottish Football League]] | work=scottishfootballleague.com | date=20 April 2013 | accessdate=27 July 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512151759/http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/football/first/results/3520276/ | archivedate=12 May 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> The title win meant Thistle returned to the top flight of Scottish football for the first time in nine years.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.scotsman.com/the-scotsman/sport/football/partick-thistle-on-spl-brink-after-nine-year-exile-1-2896891 | title=Partick Thistle on SPL brink after nine-year exile | publisher=[[The Scotsman]] | work=scotsman.com | date=16 April 2013 | accessdate=21 April 2013}}</ref> The team also lost the [[2013 Scottish Challenge Cup Final|Scottish Challenge Cup final]] to [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] on penalties in April 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/22043859 | title=Queen of the South 1\u20131 Partick Thistle (6\u20135 on pens) | publisher=[[BBC]] | date=7 April 2013 | accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> \n\nThistle's initial return to the Premiership had mixed success. The team managed to maintain a relatively positive away record, however it was months before Thistle finally secured a home win, with them beating [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] 3\u20131 at [[Firhill Stadium|Firhill]] in February 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sutherland|first1=Jonathan|title=Partick Thistle earned their first home win of the season with a rousing performance against Aberdeen|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26202557|website=www.bbc.co.uk/sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref> Thistle managed to avoid the relegation and play-off spots, eventually finishing third-bottom, following a 4\u20132 win away to [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] at [[Tynecastle Stadium|Tynecastle]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Partick Thistle sealed their Premiership safety after producing a stunning second-half comeback to get the better of Hearts|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27216438|website=www.bbc.co.uk/sport| publisher=BBC|accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref> Thistle announced the club were completely free of debt in November 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=PARTICK THISTLE NOW FREE OF DEBT|url=https://spfl.co.uk/news/partick-thistle-now-free-of-debt|publisher=[[SPFL]]|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2015\u201316 Scottish Premiership]] season saw Thistle secure long-term contracts for many of their key players, including [[Kris Doolan]], [[Callum Booth]], [[Tom\u00e1\u0161 \u010cern\u00fd]] and [[Mustapha Dumbuya]].\n\nOn 7 May 2016, Thistle secured their Premiership status with a 2\u20130 away victory to [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]], with goals coming from [[Steven Lawless]] and [[Kris Doolan]]. This result meant that Archibald overtook former manager [[Davie McParland]] as the record holder of top-flight victories. On 8 April 2017, Thistle beat [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] 1\u20130 to secure a place in the top six for the first time since the league split was first introduced to the Scottish top flight in [[2000\u201301 Scottish Premier League|2000\u201301]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39463929 | title=Partick Thistle 1\u20130 Motherwell | publisher=[[BBC]] | date=8 April 2017 | accessdate=8 April 2017}}</ref> \n\nIn the [[2017\u201318 Scottish Premiership]], Thistle finished in 11th position, narrowly avoiding 12th place with [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]] being automatically relegated. Thistle subsequently went into the Scottish Premiership play-offs against [[Livingston F.C.|Livingston]], who had finished second in the [[Scottish Championship]] in their first season of returning to the league. On 17 May 2018, Thistle lost the first leg 2\u20131 away at [[Almondvale Stadium]], with [[Kris Doolan]] getting Thistle's goal.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dowden|first1=Martin|title=Livingston 2 \u2013 1 Partick Thistle|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44063769|website=www.bbc.co.uk/sport|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> Livingston then came to face Thistle at Firhill on 20 May 2018. Livingston won the away leg 0\u20131 after [[Keaghan Jacobs]] scored in the 46th minute.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McLauchlin|first1=Brian|title=Partick Thistle 0 \u2013 1 Livingston|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44097532|website=www.bbc.co.uk/sport|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Thistle were relegated to the [[Scottish Championship]] after a stay in the top flight of five years. Subsequently, speculation surrounded whether or not Archibald would remain as Thistle's manager. On 24 May, Thistle announced on their website Archibald would remain as Partick Thistle's manager going into the Championship next season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Archibald to stay as manager as Thistle plots way back to Premiership|url=https://ptfc.co.uk/ptfc-news/archibald-to-stay-as-manager-as-thistle-plots-way-back-to-premiership/|website=www.ptfc.co.uk|publisher=Partick Thistle F.C.}}</ref> As a result of Thistle's poor season, a number of players were not offered a new contract by the club including captain [[Abdul Osman]], [[Callum Booth]], [[Steven Lawless]], [[Mustapha Dumbuya]], [[Paul McGinn]] and [[Ryan Scully]]. Transfer listed players were [[Adam Barton (footballer)|Adam Barton]], [[Niall Keown]] and [[Miles Storey]]. Australian midfielder [[Ryan Edwards (Australian footballer)|Ryan Edwards]] triggered a relegation contract clause, allowing him to leave the club immediately.<ref>{{cite web|title=Playing Squad Update|url=https://ptfc.co.uk/ptfc-news/playing-squad-update/|website=www.ptfc.co.uk|publisher=Partick Thistle F.C.|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> After a poor start to their [[2018\u201319 Scottish Championship]] season, Archibald was sacked as manager on 6 October 2018 following a 2\u20130 loss to [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]].\n\n===Gary Caldwell (2018\u20132019) ===\n[[File:Gary Caldwell Manager.jpg|thumb|right|Gary Caldwell took over in 2018.]]\nOn 15 October 2018, Thistle announced that former [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] and [[Scotland National Football Team|Scotland]] international [[Gary Caldwell]] had been appointed as Archibald's replacement. Chairman Jacqui Low said \"Put simply, he plans to build a strong defence that allows us to then push forward and play attacking football.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Gary Caldwell: Partick Thistle appoint former Wigan manager as new boss |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45855105 |website=www.bbc.co.uk/sport |accessdate=18 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThistle\u2019s first season in the [[Scottish Championship]] after relegation was a difficult one; the club were one of the promotion favourites but after a poor first half of the season they were sitting bottom by December and facing the possibility of back to back relegations.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46657160</ref> Caldwell performed a large squad overhaul in January with the key signing of [[Scott McDonald]] who went on to score 7 goals in 13 games.<ref>https://mobile.twitter.com/PartickThistle/status/1126051512420114435</ref> Caldwell managed to turn the season around with the club finishing in 6th position and avoiding further relegation to [[Scottish League One|League One]] with a 3\u20130 away win to [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] thus removing the threat of the relegation play-offs.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48075231</ref> Although safe, Caldwell released striker [[Kris Doolan]] who ended his decade-long stay at the club after being informed that his contract would not be renewed. Other players to depart included [[Miles Storey]], [[Scott McDonald]], [[Niall Keown]] and [[Souleymane Coulibaly]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Playing Squad Update |url=https://ptfc.co.uk/ptfc-news/playing-squad-update-2/ |website=www.ptfc.co.uk |publisher=Partick Thistle |accessdate=9 May 2019}}</ref> Thistle made another poor start to the Championship season, picking up 2 points in the opening 5 games. Following a 1\u20131 draw away to Arbroath Caldwell was sacked as manager.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gary Caldwell sacked as Partick Thistle boss|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49743836 |website=www.bbc.co.uk/sport |accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Ian McCall return (2019\u2013present)===\n[[File:PartickWarmup.jpeg|thumb|right|Thistle warm up in 2019]]\nAfter the sacking of Caldwell, Partick Thistle approached Ayr United on 21 September 2019 to request permission to speak to their manager Ian McCall about a potential return as manager of Thistle, which Ayr United granted. McCall announced to the press that he would make a decision in the following 24 hours. The following day it was announced by Ayr United that McCall had left the club to take over as the new manager of Partick Thistle. He was officially appointed on 23 September 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Partick Thistle: Ian McCall appointed manager after Ayr United exit |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49798938 |website=www.bbc.co.uk/sport |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, majority shareholder and lifelong Jags fan Colin Weir died at the age of 71. A minute\u2019s applause was observed at the following Thistle game against [[Greenock Morton]] for his numerous contributions to the club.<ref>{{cite web |title=Colin Weir: \u00a3161m Euromillions winner dies aged 71 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-50930002 |website=www.bbc.co.uk/news |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Minute's applause to be held at Partick Thistle game in memory of Colin Weir |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/people/minute-s-applause-to-be-held-at-partick-thistle-game-in-memory-of-colin-weir-1-5067643 |website=www.scotsman.com |publisher=The Scotsman |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe January 2020 transfer window brought new additions to the club. Strikers [[Brian Graham (footballer)|Brian Graham]] and [[Zak Rudden]] joined alongside loanees [[Jamie Barjonas]], [[Lee O'Connor (footballer)|Lee O\u2019Connor]] and Lewis Mayo. [[Darian MacKinnon]] and [[Darren Brownlie]] also joined whilst players including [[Kenny Miller]], [[Gary Harkins]] and [[Craig Slater]] ended their time at Firhill.<ref>{{cite web |title=Scottish Championship ins and outs \u2013 January 2020 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51181442 |website=www.bbc.co.uk/sport |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe start of the new decade brought little success to an already-struggling Thistle side, including a 4\u20131 home defeat to [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] and poor away performances to [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]] and [[Arbroath F.C.|Arbroath]]. Thistle were knocked out of the [[Scottish Cup]] in a 2\u20131 home defeat against [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Leigh Griffiths scores in Scottish Cup win |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/partick-vs-celtic/report/421468 |website=www.skysports.com |publisher=Sky Sports |accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>, and later eliminated from the [[Scottish Challenge Cup]] by [[Scottish League One]] side [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Raith Rovers survived a late rally from second-tier Partick Thistle to reach the Scottish Challenge Cup final. |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51466144 |website=www.bbc.co.uk/sport |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Club crest and colours==\n[[File:Partick_Thistle_Kit_Badge_1978-1990.svg|thumb|left|Kit badge from 1978 until 1990]]\n[[File:Partick Thistle FC logo (1990-2008).svg|thumb|upright|right|Logo from 1990 until 2008]]\nThe first crest to appear on a Partick Thistle kit was a thistle design, and every logo since has featured a thistle. The thistle appeared first in 1902, then again in 1909. It remained until 1978, when a new logo with the thistle housed inside a roundel was used. A modernist logo with the thistle on a rectangle was introduced in 1990, and the current crest was introduced in 2008.<ref name = \"HFK\">{{cite web|title=Partick Thistle|url=http://historicalkits.co.uk/Scottish_Football_League/Partick_Thistle/Partick_Thistle.htm|accessdate=18 October 2012|work=Historical Football Kits|first=Dave|last=Moor}}</ref>\n\nThe Jags flirted with a number of colour schemes in their early years. From their inception until 1900 the kits were predominantly blue with red and white trimmings. There was then a brief period in which the players wore an orange and black striped top with white shorts and black socks. This was replaced in 1905 by a colour scheme close to that used by [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], before the club reverted to the predominantly blue kits in 1909. In season 1936\u201337 they changed to, and settled upon, the red-yellow-and-black attire for which they are best known, this change having been triggered initially by the club borrowing kits from the local rugby union team, [[West of Scotland F.C.|West of Scotland Football Club.]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Partick Thistle \u2013 Historical Football Kits|url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Scottish_Football_League/Partick_Thistle/Partick_Thistle.htm|website=www.historicalkits.co.uk|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008\u201309 and 2009\u201310, Thistle became the first football club in Scotland to use pink as the primary colour in their away kit. In 2008\u201309 this took the form of silver- and pink-hooped tops.\n\nSince the 2013\u201314 season, Partick Thistle's kits have been manufactured by [[Joma|Joma Sports]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2013-2014/june_2013/joma_have_arrived|title=Joma Have Arrived|author=Partick Thistle FC|work=Partick Thistle FC}}</ref> During the 2014\u201315 season, Partick Thistle supported the [[Breast Cancer Care|Breast Cancer Care Charity]] by wearing a black and pink away shirt, with the charity ribbon on the shirt. The partnership saw a portion of kit sale revenue being donated to Breast Cancer Care.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/partick-thistle-unveil-breast-cancer-away-strip-1-3479897|title=Partick Thistle unveil breast cancer away strip|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nFor the [[2019\u201320 in Scottish football|2019\u201320 Season]], Partick Thistle released their new away kit which featured a [[Rainbow flag]] design under the sleeves to show support for the [[LGBT]] movement. By doing so, they became the first Scottish club to incorporate the flag on a football jersey. Club executive [[Gerry Britton]] said: \"We are really pleased with how the strips look and hope the supporters will like them as much as we do. We were very clear when putting together the design, that we wanted to make a statement about inclusivity and that\u2019s what inspired the rainbow feature on the away shirt.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ali |first1=Aftab |title=Praise for Partick Thistle as it launches away kit with LGBT+ flag colours |url=https://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/17715690.praise-for-partick-thistle-as-it-launches-away-kit-with-lgbt-flag-colours/ |website=www.eveningtimes.co.uk |publisher=Evening Times |accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Stadium==\n{{Main|Firhill Stadium}} \n[[File:Firhill2020.jpeg|thumb|right|Firhill in March 2020]]\nBefore moving to the [[Maryhill]] area in 1909, Partick Thistle hosted their home games over numerous sites in and around [[Glasgow]] including [[Kelvingrove Park]], Jordanvale Park and Muir Park. In 1897, the club moved to [[Meadowside]], near the [[River Clyde]]. However, in 1908 Thistle were forced to vacate the area to make way for a new shipyard.\n\nAfter playing at numerous other grounds in Glasgow, [[Greenock]], [[Port Glasgow]], [[Kilmarnock]], [[Edinburgh]] and even [[Aberdeen]] for over a season,<ref name=UD>Paul Smith & Shirley Smith (2005) ''The Ultimate Directory of English & Scottish Football League Grounds Second Edition 1888\u20132005'', Yore Publications, p197 {{ISBN|0954783042}}</ref> Partick Thistle moved to their present home, [[Firhill Stadium]], in 1909, when they purchased some spare [[Caledonian Railway]] land in Maryhill for \u00a35,500.<ref name=\"inglis459\">{{harvnb|Inglis|1996|p=459}}</ref> The stadium consists of three stands: the Main Stand which was built in 1927 and can seat around 2,900 supporters; the Jackie Husband Stand, which was built in 1994 and has a capacity of approximately 6,500; and the North Stand, renamed the ''John Lambie Stand'' in 2018 in tribute to the legendary club manager who passed away that year, which can house around 2,000 supporters. On the south side of the stadium there is a grass embankment, known to home fans as \"The Bing\", which had been open terracing until this was demolished in 2006 due to the stand failing to meet the criteria of [[Scottish Football Association]] safety regulations. There have been various plans to redevelop the south end of the stadium but thus far none have come to fruition.\n\n[[File:Firhill Stadium (PTFC vs St Mirren).jpg|thumb|left|Firhill Stadium]]\nFirhill has been used by other football teams and for rugby over the years. Between 1986 and 1991 [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]] ground shared with Thistle,<ref name = \"inglis459\"/> following their eviction from [[Shawfield Stadium|Shawfield]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/clyde-fans-set-to-vote-on-relocation-1-2902505 | title=Clyde fans set to vote on relocation | publisher=[[The Scotsman]] | work=scotsman.com | date=19 April 2013 | accessdate=27 July 2013}}</ref> [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]] also ground shared for two spells over seven years,<ref name=\"Club History\">{{cite web | url=http://www.hamiltonadvertiser.co.uk/hamilton-accies/2001/10/12/club-history-50144-11362323/ | title=Club History | publisher=Hamilton Advertiser | work=hamiltonadvertiser.co.uk | accessdate=27 July 2013}}</ref> following them being forced out of [[Douglas Park]] in 1994. In December 2005, Firhill also became the home of Glasgow's professional rugby union team, [[Glasgow Warriors]], when they moved from their previous base at [[Hughenden Stadium]]. After returning to Hughenden in 2006, the Warriors took up a two-year residency at Firhill from the start of the [[2007\u201308 Celtic League]] season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stv.tv/content/sport/exclusive/display.html?id=opencms:/sport/exclusive/Partick_Thistle_interviews_210607 |title=Firhill pitch can cope with rugby, insists chairman |work=www.stv.tv |publisher=STV |accessdate=8 October 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930171709/http://www.stv.tv/content/sport/exclusive/display.html?id=opencms%3A%2Fsport%2Fexclusive%2FPartick_Thistle_interviews_210607 |archivedate=30 September 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This was extended in April 2009 for a further five years.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rumsby |first=Ben |url=http://sport.scotsman.com/rugby/Glasgow-to-stay-at-Firhill.5151369.jp |title=Glasgow to stay at Firhill for next five years \u2013 Scotsman.com Sport |publisher=Sport.scotsman.com |date= |accessdate=19 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.magnersleague.com/570_2033.php | title = Warriors look to create fortress at Firhill | work = Magners League Official Website | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070707133804/http://www.magnersleague.com/570_2033.php | archivedate = 7 July 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Glasgow Warriors left Firhill after the 2011\u201312 season and moved to [[Scotstoun Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.glasgowwarriors.org/content/view/2624/48/|title=Statement from Glasgow Warriors and Scottish Rugby on Scotstoun Stadium|date=30 September 2011|accessdate=14 July 2012|work=www.glasgowwarriors.org|publisher=Glasgow Warriors}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/mobile/sport/rugby/early-season-ticket-sales-rise-500-as-glasgow-settle-in-at-scotstoun.17998060|title=Early season-ticket sales rise 500% as Glasgow settle in at Scotstoun|work=The Herald|publisher=Herald & Times Group|date=28 June 2012|accessdate=14 July 2012|first=Alasdair|last=Reid}}</ref> During the 2012\u201313 season the ground was also used by [[Celtic F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Celtic's under-20 squad]] as their home ground,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/sport/celts-deal-a-lifeline-for-jags-nextgen.18669556 | title=Celts deal a lifeline for Jags' NextGen | publisher=Evening Times | work=eveningtimes.co.uk | date=23 August 2013 | accessdate=27 July 2013}}</ref> but following Thistle's promotion this stopped for the 2013\u201314 season.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2012-2013/may_2013/pitch_update | title=Pitch Update | publisher=Partick Thistle | work=ptfc.co.uk | date=14 May 2013 | accessdate=27 July 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130714014538/http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2012-2013/may_2013/pitch_update | archivedate=14 July 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2013\u201314 season, the Main Stand was re-opened to seat the high number of away supporters. In one instance, the North Stand was used for [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] supporters as fears grew over fire dangers. During early June 2016 the Main Stand was renamed The ''Colin Weir Stand'' in honour of Colin Weir who was made the first ever patron of Partick Thistle after making numerous donations to the club's [[youth system]], the ''Thistle Weir Academy''.\n\nOn the [[Glasgow Subway]] network, [[Kelvinbridge subway station|Kelvinbridge]] and [[St George's Cross subway station|St George's Cross]] are within 15 minutes walk of the stadium.<ref name = \"sfgg\"/> The [[A81 road]] (Maryhill Road), leading to Firhill Road, runs from the [[M8 motorway (Scotland)|M8 motorway]] and is also the route of several local buses from the city centre.<ref name = \"sfgg\"/> {{rws|Maryhill}} and {{rws|Possilpark & Parkhouse}}, served by trains from [[Glasgow Queen Street railway station|Glasgow Queen Street]], are the nearest railway stations to Firhill, but are not particularly close; the walk between the two sites takes around 30 minutes.<ref name = \"sfgg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.footballgroundguide.com/scotland/partick_thistle.htm |accessdate=14 July 2012 |title=Partick Thistle|publisher=Scottish Football Ground Guide }}</ref>\n\n===Training facilities===\nFor many years, Thistle struggled to find a permanent training ground at which to base themselves. Subsequently, the club relied on independently owned facilities that usually restricted Thistle's ability to train freely.\n\nAs of 2014, the club trained at the [[University of Glasgow]]'s ''Garscube Sports Complex'' on the northern periphery of the city (near [[Bearsden]], [[East Dunbartonshire]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/new-training-ground-help-partick-3797604 |title=New training ground will help Partick attract new players, says Jags boss Alan Archibald | publisher=Daily Record |work=dailyrecord.co.uk | date=2 June 2014 | accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nThistle's fortunes improved however in April 2017, the month they secured their top-six Premiership status. Millionaire couple Colin and Christine Weir invested in the club again, allowing plans for a new \u00a34 million purpose-built training centre for the club to use as a permanent base. Thistle expected to lease this from the Weirs' company ''Three Black Cats''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goodlad|first1=Phil|title=Partick Thistle secure funding for \u00a34m training centre to build on top-six spot|url=http://m.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/39567922|website=www.bbcsport.co.uk|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, it was announced that the new training facility would be named after Thistle\u2019s [[1971 Scottish League Cup Final]] manager [[Davie McParland]], who died just days after the announcement was made. The new facility was to be located near the town [[Kirkintilloch]]. Plans for the new facility were abandoned in December 2019 as the investment money was instead used by Colin Weir to purchase the club and to operate a fan-owned business model. A short time after this announcement, Weir died at the age of 71.<ref>{{cite web |title=Partick Thistle shelve training ground plan after Colin Weir takeover. |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50690799 |website=www.bbc.co.uk/sport |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable former players==\n[[File:Doolan applaud.jpg|thumb|right|Striker [[Kris Doolan]] became the most recent inductee to the club hall of fame in 2019. This was to be his final year at the club after a decade-long stay.]]\nAll former players or managers listed have been inducted into either the [[Scottish Football Hall of Fame]] or Partick Thistle's own Hall of Fame. These include players who participated in both the [[1920\u201321 Scottish Cup|1921 Scottish Cup Final]] and the [[1971\u201372 Scottish League Cup|1971 Scottish League Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Hall of Fame|url=http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2011-2012/october_2011/hall_of_fame|website=www.ptfc.co.uk|publisher=Partick Thistle F.C.|accessdate=10 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hall of Fame inductee|url=http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2010-2011/november_2010/hall_of_fame_inductee|website=www.ptfc.co.uk|publisher=Partick Thistle F.C.|accessdate=10 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Scottish Hall of Fame===\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Alan Hansen]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Mo Johnston]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Alan Rough]]\n\n===Club Hall of Fame===\nPartial list of those in the Club Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ptfc.co.uk/club/about-us/hall-of-fame/|title=PFTC Hall of Fame}}</ref>\n\n{{col-begin}}\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Alan Archibald]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Kenny Arthur]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Bertie Auld]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Gerry Britton]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Chic Charnley]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Nobby Clark (footballer)|Nobby Clark]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Kris Doolan]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} Neil Duffy\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Bobby Houston (footballer, born 1952)|Bobby Houston]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Jackie Husband]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[John Lambie (footballer, born 1940)|John Lambie]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} Bobby Law\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Danny Lennon]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Peter McKennan]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[John Mackenzie (footballer)|Johnny McKenzie]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Davie McParland]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Denis McQuade]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Alex O'Hara]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Alex Rae (footballer, born 1946)|Alex Rae]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Doug Somner]]\n* {{Flagicon|Scotland}} [[Kenny Watson (footballer)|Kenny Watson]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Club culture and fanbase==\n[[File:Thistle vs Killie.jpg|thumb|Thistle playing [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] in the [[Scottish Premiership]](September 2013)]]\n\nThe club has a relatively modest fanbase which is mostly centred around Northern Glasgow, although they do have pockets of fans from across the globe.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scotlandnow.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/meet-partick-thistle-fans-who-5008157|title=Meet the Partick Thistle fans who support their team from across the globe|first=Harry|last=McGrath|date=20 January 2015|publisher=}}</ref> Being in close proximity to a large student population the club attracts many new fans from the local universities.\n\nThe club prides itself on being [[Sectarianism in Glasgow|non-sectarian]]<ref>Geopolitics: Re-Visioning World Politics by John Agnew, Routledge, 1 Mar 2004</ref> and, therefore, not involved in the [[Old Firm]] division.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nSince the 1980s, the club has a small [[Football hooliganism|hooligan firm]] called the ''North Glasgow Express''.<ref>Celtic Soccer Crew: What the Hell Do We Care? by John O'Kane, 19 April 2012, John Blake Publishing, Chapter: Other firms</ref><ref name=Airdrie/>\n\n===Rivalries===\nAlthough the club competes with neighbours [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] and [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], due to the vast differences in team size and fortunes those rivalries are not reciprocated. The \"Glasgow derby\" is therefore contested with [[Clyde F.C.|Clyde]], sometimes dubbed the \"Old Firm alternative\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glasgowlive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/clyde-partick-thistle-set-kick-11696353|title=The ones to watch as Clyde take on Partick Thistle in the Irn Bru Cup|first=David|last=Brockett|date=2 August 2016|publisher=}}</ref>  One of the fiercest rivals were [[Airdrieonians F.C.|Airdrieonians]] with past violent clashes between fans including Airdrie's [[Section B]] group, however this rivalry has faded with time.<ref name=Airdrie>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/man-seriously-hurt-in-street-battle-1021915|title=Man seriously hurt in street battle between Partick Thistle and Airdrie United fans|date=8 May 2009|accessdate=21 April 2019|publisher=Daily Record}}</ref> Strong rivalries also existed with [[Clydebank F.C.|Clydebank]] due to the geographic proximity and controversial ownership in the past (with plans which almost saw both clubs bankrupt); and local rivals [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsc.co.uk/the-archive/950-the-five-minute/2926-partick-thistle|title=When Saturday Comes \u2013 Partick Thistle|first=Chris|last=Fyfe|publisher=}}</ref> A more modern rivalry the club has is with Greenock Morton, which stemmed from the 2012\u201313 title race; Thistle won the First Division and Morton finished runners-up.\n\n===Chants===\nThistle fans sing songs during matches, some of which are relatively generic but others which are unique. Choruses of \"He Wears Number 9\", \"Rellow Army\", \"Mary fae Maryhill\", \"Over Land and Sea\", \"Forever and Ever\", \"We've Followed the Thistle for Many a Day\", \"Oh Maryhill is wonderful\", \u201cWe\u2019re a well known Glasgow Football Team\u201d, \"Super [[Ian McCall (footballer)|Ian McCall]]\", and \"[[Gerry Britton]] is the King of Spain\" are commonly heard in the singing section of the home support, in the John Lambie stand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2012-2013/august_2012/standing_room_only |title=Standing Room Only \u2013 Partick Thistle Football Club |publisher=Ptfc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Attendances===\nDuring their previous foray into the top flight of Scottish football in season 2002\u201303 attendances exceeded 6,000, whereas in the lower divisions they have tended to range between 2,000 and 4,000.\n\nDuring the Jags' title winning campaign of 2012\u201313, a match of significant importance was played against Greenock Morton; the attendance was 8,875 which was the biggest First Division crowd that season.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/22057991 Partick Thistle 1\u20130 Morton] BBC Sport, 10 April 2013</ref>\n\nOn the day of their return to the top flight against [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] on 2 August 2013, the attendance at [[Firhill]] was 7,822.<ref>{{cite web|title=Partick Thistle v Dundee United, 2nd August 2013|url=http://ptfc.co.uk/teams/senior/seasons/2013-2014/fixtures_results/0208_dundee_united|website=www.ptfc.co.uk|publisher=Partick Thistle F.C.|accessdate=11 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112014444/http://ptfc.co.uk/teams/senior/seasons/2013-2014/fixtures_results/0208_dundee_united|archive-date=12 November 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Average home attendances for Thistle's maiden season back in the [[Scottish Premiership]] was around 5,000, however the 2014\u201315 season saw a 25% drop with an average home crowd of only 3,500.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/clubs/celtic/302136-how-has-your-clubs-average-attendance-changed-in-past-20-years |title=How Has Your Club's Average Attendances Changed in the Past 20 Years |publisher=Stv.co.uk |date= |accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Notable supporters===\n*[[Mhairi Black]], MP for Paisley & Renfrewshire South.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/08/snp-mhairi-black-20-labour-student-mp|title=Mhairi Black: the 20-year-old who beat a Labour heavyweight|author=Ewen MacAskill|work=the Guardian}}</ref>\n*[[Maryhill]] born actor [[Robert Carlyle]] ([[Trainspotting (film)|Trainspotting]], [[The Full Monty]] and [[The 51st State]]) is also a famous supporter, stating he would rather watch the Jags than watch [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] or [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=McDonald|first1=Toby|title=Robert Carlyle: I get more thrills watching Partick Thistle than Manchester United|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/robert-carlyle-i-get-more-thrills-watching-1001665|publisher=|work=Daily Record|accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Craig Ferguson]], former host of the popular American chat show ''[[The Late Late Show with Craig Ferguson]]''.<ref name = \"fans\">{{cite news |url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/odd/david-hasselhoff-tweets-support-for-partick-thistle-1-3968841 |title=David Hasselhoff tweets support for Partick Thistle |work=The Scotsman |publisher= |date=7 December 2015 |accessdate=29 January 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Laura Kuenssberg]], [[BBC]] Political editor.<ref name = \"fans\"/>\n*The historian [[Niall Ferguson]] was a supporter while growing up in Glasgow.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Templeton|first1=Tom|title=This Much I Know, Niall Ferguson|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2009/jan/18/niall-ferguson-historian-interview|website=www.theguardian.com|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref>\n*''[[Hollyoaks]]'' actor [[Chris Fountain]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Football Scarf in the colours of|url=http://www.appleberry.co.uk/partick-thistle-scarf/135|website=www.appleberry.co.uk|accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref>\n*American actor [[David Hasselhoff]] said he is a fan of the club, and likes the club's values. Mr Hasselhoff also met some of the team for a live TV interview.<ref>https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/row-zed/david-hasselhoff-professes-love-partick-7052897</ref>\n*Jack Revill, DJ from Glasgow better known as [[Jackmaster]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://noisey.vice.com/fr/article/r7v59x/jackmaster-numbers-glasgow-dj-interview|title=Jackmaster a trois amours : Glasgow, la house et les maillots de foot des ann\u00e9es 90|date=2015-02-05|work=Noisey|access-date=2018-02-18|language=fr}}</ref>\n*Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] was pictured wearing a Partick Thistle scarf on a train and has mentioned the club in the past.<ref>http://www.deadlinenews.co.uk/2017/06/12/jezzas-jag-corbyn-sports-partick-thistle-scarf-snap-train/</ref>\n*Former Tennis player [[Colin Fleming]] is a self proclaimed Jags fan, following in his family's footsteps as he attended games when he was younger and kept track of Thistle's results while on tour.   <ref>https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/15374437.my-sporting-saturday-colin-fleming-on-mixing-his-love-of-tennis-and-thistle/</ref>\n\n==Sponsors==\nThe club's main sponsor is Just Employment Law, taking over from Kingsford Capital Management. MacB resumed sponsorship of Partick Thistle in the summer of 2012, and subsequently signed a two-year extension, keeping them as main sponsors until the end of the 2014\u201315 season. Scottish security system company Alarmfast also started sponsoring Thistle for the 2014\u201315 season.\n\nThistle's kit maker is Spanish manufacturers [[Joma]], having replaced [[Puma Sports]] at the start of the 2013\u201314 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Joma Have Arrived at Firhill|url=http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2013-2014/june_2013/joma_have_arrived|website=www.ptfc.co.uk|publisher=Partick Thistle Football Club|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{clear right}}\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed plainrowheaders\" style=\"width: 25%; text-align: centr; margin-left:1em; float: left\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Kit suppliers\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Dates\n! scope=\"col\" |Supplier\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |1977\u20131983\n| [[Umbro]]\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |1983\u20131984\n| Unbranded\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |1984\u20131989\n| [[Umbro]]\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |1989\u20131983\n| Spall Sports\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |1993\u20131994\n| [[Bukta]]\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |1994\u20131995\n| Matchwinner\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |1995\u20131997\n| [[Le Coq Sportif]]\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |1997\u20131999\n| Arrow\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |1999\u20132000\n| Rossco\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |2000\u20132002\n| Secca Sports\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |2002\u20132006\n| TFG Sports\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |2006\u20132008\n| [[Diadora]]\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |2008\u20132013\n| [[Puma SE|Puma]]\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |2013\u2013\n| [[Joma]]\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed plainrowheaders\" style=\"width: 25%; text-align: centr; margin-left:1em; float: left\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Shirt sponsors<ref name=\"Partick Thistle home historical kits\">{{cite web |url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Scottish_Football_League/Partick_Thistle/Partick_Thistle.htm |accessdate=11 January 2016|title=Partick Thistle |website=Historical Football Kits}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Dates\n! scope=\"col\" |Sponsor\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |1983\u20131986\n| Morton Rolls\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |1986\u20131987\n| Ashoka West End\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |1987\u20131989\n| Colonel Gee's Carpets\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |1989\u20131990\n| Watson Towers\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |1990\u20131996\n| Texstyle World\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |1996\u20131997\n| DLS\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |1997\u20131999\n| [[Auto Windscreens]]\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |1999\u20132007\n| D.H.Morris Group\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |2007\u20132008\n| Resolution Asset Management\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |2008\u20132011\n| Ignis Asset Management\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |2011\u20132012\n| MacB Water\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |2012\n| Just Employment Law\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |2012\u20132015\n| MacB Water\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |2015\u20132018\n| Kingsford Capital Management\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" |2018\u2013\n| Just Employment Law\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Mascot==\n[[File:KingsleyMascot.jpg|thumb|Kingsley at a media event in [[George Square]], Glasgow]]\nPartick Thistle's current mascot is named Kingsley, and was designed by the [[Turner Prize]]-nominated artist [[David Shrigley]]. Kingsley was unveiled on 22 June 2015 to coincide with Thistle's new sponsorship with [[California]]-based investment firm Kingsford Capital Management.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kingsford Capital Management to be Jags New Title Sponsor|url=http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2015-2016/june_2015/kingsford_capital_management_to_be_jags_new_title_sponsor|website=ptfc.co.uk|accessdate=23 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150622162107/http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2015-2016/june_2015/kingsford_capital_management_to_be_jags_new_title_sponsor|archive-date=22 June 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Kingsley succeeded [[Jaggy MacBee]], a bumble bee who had been the club's mascot from 2011 to 2015, as part of the club's sponsorship with Scottish beverage company MacB.<ref>{{cite news|title=Macb water sponsors Patrick Thistle football club|url=http://www.talkingretail.com/products-news/macb-water-sponsors-patrick-thistle-football-club/|accessdate=11 January 2016|work=Talking Retail|date=16 June 2011}}</ref> Prior to that the mascot was a brightly-coloured toucan called Pee Tee.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hM28BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT197&lpg=PT197&dq=pee+tee+partick+thistle#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Hunting Grounds: A Scottish Football Safari|last=Sutherland|first=Gary|date=2012-08-10|publisher=Birlinn|isbn=9780857901187|language=en}}</ref>\n\nKingsley gained widespread notoriety online, having trended worldwide on [[Twitter]], as well as being publicised by major networks such as [[CNN]] and ''[[The Washington Post]]'',<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/early-lead/wp/2015/06/22/partick-thistle-fcs-new-mascot-will-haunt-your-dreams/ | work=The Washington Post | first=Matt | last=Bonesteel | title=Partick Thistle FC's new mascot will haunt your dreams |date=22 June 2015}}</ref> [[CNN]] and [[TIME Magazine]].<ref>{{cite news|title=This Soccer Team\u2019s New Mascot Will Haunt Your Every Waking Moment|url=http://time.com/3930288/partick-thistle-mascot/|website=time.com|accessdate=23 June 2015|first=Alexandra|last=Sifferlin|date=22 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Partick Thistle's new mascot Kingsley: Scary or sun-like?|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/06/22/football/partick-thistle-kingsley-mascot-football/|website=edition.cnn.com|accessdate=23 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Everyone's talking about Kingsley, Partick Thistle's new mascot designed by David Shrigley|url=http://www.thedrum.com/news/2015/06/22/everyones-talking-about-kingsley-partick-thistles-new-mascot-designed-david-shrigley|website=www.thedrum.com|accessdate=23 June 2015}}</ref> The launch, and subsequent pictures, appeared across the UK media including in [[The Daily Telegraph]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Partick Thistle unveil utterly terrifying new mascot|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/babb/11691493/Partick-Thistle-unveil-utterly-terrifying-new-mascot.html|accessdate=23 June 2015 | location=London|work=The Daily Telegraph|first=JJ|last=Bull|date=22 June 2015}}</ref> The Times, [[BBC]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Partick Thistle unveil 'terrifying' new mascot Kingsley \u2013 BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-33225555|website=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=23 June 2015|date=22 June 2015}}</ref> [[Sky Sports]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Is Partick Thistle mascot Kingsley the scariest ever?|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/29032/9893109/is-partick-thistle-mascot-kingsley-the-scariest-ever|website=www.skysports.com, accessdate: 23 June 2015}}</ref> [[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]],<ref>{{cite web|title=From San Francisco to Firhill: The story of Kingsley the Partick Thistle mascot|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/football/from-san-francisco-to-firhill-the-story-of-kingsley-the-partick-thistle-mascot.129742379|website=www.heraldscotland.com|accessdate=23 June 2015}}</ref> The Sun and [[Talk Sport]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Partick Thistle's new mascot \u2013 the best reaction to 'Kingsley' |url=http://talksport.com/football/partick-thistles-new-mascot-best-reaction-kingsley-150622151731|website=talksport.com|accessdate=23 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nPartick Thistle's general manager [[Ian Maxwell (footballer)|Ian Maxwell]] hailed the success of Kingsley in drawing attention to the club, stating that the worldwide interest and TV coverage amounted to the \"biggest amount of publicity from a sponsorship launch in Scottish football history\".<ref name=\"mskt\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/partick-thistles-new-mascot-kingsley-5958096 |accessdate=11 January 2016 |first=Gordon |last=Parks |title=Partick Thistle's new mascot Kingsley proves fans want change in Scottish football, says Firhill general manager Ian Maxwell |date=27 June 2015 |work=Daily Record}}</ref> The Kingsley mascot has become a major source of merchandising potential for the club, with demand outstripping supply.<ref name=\"mskt\" />\n\n==Community trust==\n\n===Partick Thistle Women===\n{{Main|Partick Thistle W.F.C.}}\n'''Thistle Weir Ladies Football Club''' was officially founded as part of the Thistle Weir Academy in 2014, having previously existed as part of the Charitable Trust for one year prior to that.<ref name=\"name_change\">{{cite web|url=https://ptfc.co.uk/ptfc-news/thistle-weir-ladies-start-new-season-as-partick-thistle-womens-fc/|publisher=Partick Thistle F.C.|date=23 January 2019|language=|accessdate=21 February 2019|title=Thistle Weir Ladies start new season as Partick Thistle Women's Football Club}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/thistle-be-great-for-womens-football-147049n.22988400|last=Lach|first=Stef|title=Thistle be great for women's football|website=Evening Times|accessdate=23 February 2019|date=3 January 2014}}</ref>\nIn October 2018, the team gained promotion to the [[Scottish Women's Premier League 2]] (SWPL 2), which is the second highest tier for women's football in Scotland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ptfc.co.uk/ptfc-news/thistle-weir-ladies-celebrate-promotion-to-the-swpl-2/|publisher=Partick Thistle F.C.|date=22 October 2018|language=|accessdate=23 February 2019|title=Thistle Weir Ladies celebrate promotion to the SWPL 2}}</ref> In January 2019, the club rebranded as '''Partick Thistle Women's Football Club'''.<ref name=\"name_change\"/> \n\nThe team train at the Firhill Complex in Maryhill, but play their matches at [[Petershill Park]] in Springburn.\n\n===Thistle Weir Youth Academy===\nIn October 2013, millionaires and long time Thistle fans Chris and Colin Weir donated \u00a3750,000 to Partick Thistle to set up a new advanced youth academy. The academy was named the Thistle Weir Youth Academy and is run by former striker [[Gerry Britton]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Thistle Weir Youth Academy Update|url=http://ptfc.co.uk/news/2013-2014/january_2014/thistle_weir_youth_academy_update|website=www.ptfc.co.uk|publisher=Partick Thistle F.C.|accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref> Graduates of the academy include current Thistle player [[James Penrice]], [[Norwich City]] midfielder [[Aidan Fitzpatrick]], [[Melbourne City F.C.|Melbourne City]] defender [[Jack Hendry (footballer, born 1995)|Jack Hendry]] and [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline]] striker [[Kevin Nisbet]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Graduates |url=https://ptfc.co.uk/club/thistleweiracademy/graduates/ |website=www.ptfc.co.uk |publisher=Partick Thistle |accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Current squad==\n\n===First team squad===\n11:13, 21 March 2020 (UTC)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ptfc.co.uk/team/first-team/ |title=Partick Thistle squad |accessdate=31 July 2019 |website=Partick Thistle FC}}</ref>\n{{fs start}}\n{{fs player|no= 1|nat=SCO|name=[[Jamie Sneddon]]|pos=GK}}\n{{fs player|no= 2|nat=SCO|name=[[Ryan Williamson]]|pos=DF}}\n{{fs player|no= 3|nat=SCO|name=[[James Penrice]]|pos=DF}}\n{{fs player|no= 4|nat=SCO|name=[[Thomas O'Ware]]|pos=DF|other=[[Captain (association football)|captain]]}}\n{{fs player|no=5|nat=SCO|name=[[Darren Brownlie]]|pos=DF}}\n{{fs player|no=6|nat=SCO|name=[[Lewis Mayo (Scottish footballer)|Lewis Mayo]]|pos=DF|other=on loan from [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]}}\n{{fs player|no= 7|nat=ENG|name=[[Joe Cardle]]|pos=MF}}\n{{fs player|no= 8|nat=SCO|name=[[Stuart Bannigan]]|pos=MF}}\n{{fs player|no= 9|nat