te=17 November 2014}}</ref>\n|1939\u20131957\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[William Paul (footballer, born 1869)|Willie Paul]]\n|186\n|1884\u20131899\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|George Smith\n|125\n|1953\u20131964\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Jimmy Walker (footballer, born 1925)|Jimmy Walker]]\n|121\n|1946\u20131957\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Kris Doolan]]\n|121\n|2009\u20132019\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[John Torbet|Johnny Torbet]]\n|116\n|1924\u20131933\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Willie Newall\n|101\n|1938\u20131945\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Doug Somner|Dougie Somner]]\n|101\n|1974\u20131979\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Davie Ness\n|97\n|1923\u20131935\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Honours==\n[[File:Thistle crowned champs.jpg|thumbnail|380px|right|Thistle win the 2012\u201313 Scottish First Division.]]\n\n===Major===\n\n*'''[[Scottish Cup]]:'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' [[1920\u201321 Scottish Cup|1920\u201321]]\n**Runners up (1): [[1929\u201330 Scottish Cup|1929\u201330]]\n*'''[[Scottish League Cup]]:'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' [[1971\u201372 Scottish League Cup|1971\u201372]]\n**Runners up (3): [[1953\u201354 Scottish League Cup|1953\u201354]], [[1956\u201357 Scottish League Cup|1956\u201357]], [[1958\u201359 Scottish League Cup|1958\u201359]]\n\n===Minor===\n\n*'''[[Scottish Football League First Division]], second tier''':<ref name=\"2nd division\">Known as second division prior to 1975</ref>\n**'''Winners (6):''' [[1896\u201397 in Scottish football|1896\u201397]], [[1899\u20131900 in Scottish football|1899\u20131900]], [[1970\u201371_Scottish_Division_Two|1970\u201371]], [[1975\u201376 Scottish First Division|1975\u201376]], [[2001\u201302 Scottish First Division|2001\u201302]], [[2012\u201313 Scottish First Division|2012\u201313]]\n**Runners up (3): [[1901\u201302 in Scottish football|1901\u201302]], [[1991\u201392 in Scottish football|1991\u201392]], [[2008\u201309 Scottish First Division|2008\u201309]]\n*'''[[Scottish Football League Second Division]], third tier:'''\n**'''Winners:''' [[2000\u201301 in Scottish football|2000\u201301]]\n**'''Play-off Winners:''' [[2005\u201306 in Scottish football|2005\u201306]]\n*'''[[Scottish Challenge Cup]]:'''<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Stevie|title=Queen of the South lifted the Challenge Cup for the second time after a penalty shoot-out victory over Partick Thistle|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22043859|website=www.bbc.co.uk/sport|publisher=BBC|accessdate=17 November 2014}}</ref>\n**Runners up: [[2012\u201313 Scottish Challenge Cup|2012\u201313]]\n*'''[[Glasgow Cup]]:'''\n**'''Winners:''' 1934\u201335, 1950\u201351, 1952\u201353, 1954\u201355, 1960\u201361, 1980\u201381, 1988\u201389\n**Runners up (11) 1888\u201389, 1900\u201301, 1911\u201312, 1914\u201315, 1917\u201318, 1919\u201320, 1932\u201333, 1936\u201337, 1959\u201360, 1966\u201367, 1968\u201369\n*'''British Cup:'''\n**'''Winners:''' 1921\n*'''[[Glasgow Merchants Charity Cup]]:'''\n**'''Winners (3):''' 1926\u201327, 1934\u201335, 1948\u201349\n*'''[[Summer Cup (Scottish football)|Summer Cup]]:'''\n**'''Winners:''' 1945\n*'''West of Scotland FA Cup:'''\n**'''Winners: ''' 1879\n*'''Glasgow Dental Cup:'''\n**'''Winners (1):''' 1929\n*'''Greenock Charity Cup:'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/greenockcharitycup |title=Greenock Charity Cup 1884\u20131896 |publisher=Scottish-football-historical-archive.com |date= |accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref>\n**'''Winners:''' 1893\n*'''Paisley Charity Cup:'''\n**'''Winners:''' 1936\n*'''Yoker Cup:'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scottish-football-historical-archive.com/yokercup |title=Yoker Cup 1880\u20131883 |publisher=Scottish-football-historical-archive.com |date= |accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref>\n**'''Winners:''' 1881, 1882, 1883\n*'''Arr Craib Trophy:'''<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/sfl/2012/07/23/arr-craib-trophy-sean-welsh-steals-the-show-as-partick-thistle-dump-everton-to-lift-cup-86908-23911553/|title = ARR Craib Trophy: Sean Welsh steals the show as Partick Thistle dump Everton to lift cup|date = 23 July 2012|accessdate = 24 July 2012}}</ref>\n**'''Winners:''' 2012\n*'''[[Tennents' Sixes]]:'''<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bathgate|first1=Stuart|title=When winters were warmed by six appeal|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/when-winters-were-warmed-by-six-appeal-1-2734006|website=www.scotsman.com|publisher=The Scotsman|accessdate=17 November 2014}}</ref>\n**'''Winners:''' 1993 (final winners)\n\n==Club records==\n*'''Highest record home attendance:''' 49,838 vs [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], Scottish First Division, 18 February 1922<ref name=\"Rec\">{{cite web | url=http://ptfc.co.uk/club/records | title=Club Records | publisher=Partick Thistle F.C. | work=ptfc.co.uk | accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref>\n*'''Most league appearances:''' [[Alan Rough]], 410<ref name = \"Rec\"/>\n*'''Most league goals in a season:''' Alec Hair, 41, 1926\u201327<ref name = \"Rec\"/>\n*'''Record defeat:''' 0\u201310 v Queen's Park, Scottish Cup, 3 December 1881<ref name = \"Rec\"/>\n*'''Record victory:''' 16\u20130 v Royal Albert, Scottish Cup 1st round, 17 January 1931<ref name = \"Rec\"/>\n*'''Record points total:''' 78, Scottish First Division, 2012\u201313<ref name = \"Rec\"/>\n*'''Record transfer fee paid:''' \u00a385,000 to Celtic for [[Andy Murdoch (footballer, born 1970)|Andy Murdoch]], February 1991<ref name = \"Rec\"/>\n*'''Record transfer fee received:''' \u00a3350,000 from [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] for [[Liam Lindsay]], June 2017 / \u00a3350,000 from [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] for [[Aidan Fitzpatrick]], July 2019\n\n==European record==\n{{main article|Partick Thistle F.C. in European football}}\nThistle have participated in European competition on three different occasions. On the first occasion, they qualified having finished third in the First Division. They progressed to the second round of the Fairs Cup before being eliminated by [[1. FC Brno|Spartak Brno]]. They qualified for the UEFA Cup in 1972\u201373 after winning the League Cup the previous season; Hungarian side [[Budapest Honv\u00e9d FC|Honv\u00e9d]] eliminated them in the first round.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kennedy|first1=Niall|title=Partick Thistle-Club History|url=http://ptfc.co.uk/club/history|website=www.ptfc.co.uk|publisher=Partick Thistle Football Club|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> Their most recent European campaign was the [[UEFA Intertoto Cup 1995|1995 UEFA Intertoto Cup]], when they finished 4th with four points in Group 6.<ref>{{cite web|title=UEFA history \u2013 Partick Thistle|url=http://www.uefa.com/teamsandplayers/teams/club=59863/profile/history/index.html|website=www.uefa.com|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=9 November 2014}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:red; color:yellow;\" scope=\"col\"|Season\n! style=\"background:red; color:yellow;\" scope=\"col\"|Competition\n! style=\"background:red; color:yellow;\" scope=\"col\"|Round\n! style=\"background:red; color:yellow;\" scope=\"col\"|Opponent\n! style=\"background:red; color:yellow;\" scope=\"col\"|Home\n! style=\"background:red; color:yellow;\" scope=\"col\"|Away\n! style=\"background:red; color:yellow;\" scope=\"col\"|Aggregate\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[1963\u201364 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup|1963\u201364]]\n|rowspan=2|[[Inter-Cities Fairs Cup]]\n|First round\n|{{flagicon|NIR}} [[Glentoran F.C.|Glentoran]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\u20130\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\u20131\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\u20131\n|-\n|Second round\n|{{flagicon|Czechoslovakia}} [[FC Zbrojovka Brno|Spartak Brno]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\u20132\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20134\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\u20136\n|-\n|[[1972\u201373 UEFA Cup|1972\u201373]]\n|[[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]\n|First round\n|{{flagicon|HUN}} [[Budapest Honv\u00e9d FC|Budapest Honv\u00e9d]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20133\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20131\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20134\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[1995 UEFA Intertoto Cup|1995\u201396]]\n|rowspan=4|[[UEFA Intertoto Cup]]\n|rowspan=4|Group 6\n|{{flagicon|AUT}} [[LASK Linz]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2013\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\u20132\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2013\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ISL}} [[Knattspyrnudeild Keflav\u00edk|Keflav\u00edk]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\u20131\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2013\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2013\n|-\n|{{flagicon|FRA}} [[FC Metz|Metz]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2013\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|0\u20131<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.footballdatabase.eu/football.coupe.metz.partick-thistle.15522.en.html |title=European Football Database |last1=Angulo |first1=Rodrigo |date=14 October 2007 |website=www.footballdatabase.eu |publisher=FootballDatabase.eu |accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2013\n|-\n|{{flagicon|CRO}} [[NK Zagreb]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\u20132\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2013\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2013\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n;Sources\n*{{cite book| ref = harv | first = Simon | last = Inglis | title = Football Grounds of Britain | year = 1996 | publisher = Collins Willow | isbn = 978-0-00-218426-7 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Partick Thistle FC}}\n* {{official website|http://www.ptfc.co.uk}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/teams/partick-thistle BBC Sport: Partick Thistle]\n* [http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/sport/partick_thistle Evening Times: Partick Thistle]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k9ubw7aiwIo Grasping the Thistle], 2002 [[BBC Scotland]] documentary\n\n{{Partick Thistle F.C.}}\n{{Scottish Professional Football League}}\n{{Scottish Premier League}}\n{{Scottish Football League}}\n{{Glasgow}}\n{{Football in Glasgow}}\n\n[[Category:Partick Thistle F.C.| ]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1876]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:1876 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League teams]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League teams]]\n[[Category:Scottish Cup winners]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League teams]]\n[[Category:Scottish League Cup winners]]\n[[Category:Partick]]\n[[Category:Maryhill]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:8f1c:1b00:7164:ef12:fa61:e775", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partick_Thistle_F.C."}
{"title_page": "John Register", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = John Register\n| image         = \n| alt           =\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = John Sherman Register\n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = [[New York]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1939|7|29|1996|4|9}}\n| death_place   = [[Malibu]], [[California]]\n| death_cause = [[Cancer]]\n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality   = [[American]]\n| movement      = [[Realism]]\n| training      = \n| field         = Painting\n| works         = \n}}\n'''John Register''' (1939 [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] \u2013 1996 [[Malibu, California|Malibu]], [[California]]) was an American realist painter. \n\n==Background==\nJohn Sherman Register was born in New York City in 1939 to Dorothy Deming Pratt Register and Samuel Croft Register, later graduating from the [[Lawrenceville School]] in New Jersey and the [[University of California]] at Berkeley.  He later studied at the [[California School of Fine Arts]] in San Francisco. After graduating from the University of California, Berkeley, with B.A. in Literature in 1961,John Sherman Register he met his wife Catherine Richards, in a photography class at The Pasadena Art Center where he was studying commercial art. \n\nIn 1964 the two moved to New York, where Register studied design and television at the [[Pratt Institute]] (founded by his great-grandfather).<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> They married on February 6, 1964 and together had three children Peter, Kate and David. \n\nDuring this period Register pursued a career in advertising at McCaffrey and McCall. In 1972, just after his 33rd birthday,<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/>  Register left an important client meeting saying he had a dental appointment and never returning.  He subsequently became a full-time painter, moving is family to California. \n\nRegister photographed the cities they passed through, saying \"I look for offbeat beauty. I don't know what I'm looking for until I find it. There are things so ugly that I can't paint them. Sometimes I get depressed by that city, and by other cities I visit. But I like the patina of things that have been battered by life\".\nJohn Register's vision of isolated streets, empty coffee shops, long shadows, old hotels, and bus stations \"represent a haunting stillness tinged with regret and hope\", wrote Barnaby Conrad in John Register Persistent Observer.\n\nRegister was born with a genetic kidney disease and nearly died numerous times.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/>  He had suffered kidney failure 15 years before his death &mdash; ultimately from cancer from kidney transplant rejection drugs.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> In September 1994, he was told he had four to six weeks to live. He lived instead for 18 months, battling cancer until his death in 1996 at the age of 57, in Malibu, California.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> \n\nAt the time of his death, he was survived by his mother, Dorothy Pratt Barrett of Hillsborough, California; his sister, Barbara Pratt Register of Rolling Hills, California; his brother, Eliot Steven Steven Barrett of St. Helena, California; and his three children, Peter, David and Katie; and one grandson.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/>\n\n==Work==\nHe was honored with a retrospective of his career in 1999.\n\nRegister's work was used, and credited, as the inspiration for the video for \"[[Turn My Head]]\" by the band [[Live (band)|Live]] in 1997.\n\nRegister's work was also featured in the movie [[In Her Shoes (2005 film)|''In Her Shoes'' (2005 film)]].  Director [[Curtis Hanson]] liked the \"loneliness\" that Register's paintings suggested for the feel of the film.\n\n==References==\n* [[Barnaby Conrad III|Conrad, Barnaby III]]. ''John Register: Persistent Observer.'' Duane Press, 1999.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.modernisminc.com/artists/John_REGISTER/ Register at Modernism.]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928175116/http://www.sjmusart.org/content/collection/highlights/paintings/item_info.phtml?itemID=24&typeID=paintings ''Desert Landscape'' at the San Jose Museum of Art.]\n*[http://artregister.com/SeavestIntroductiontoCollection/Catalogue/RegisterConversation.html ''The Conversation'' at the Seavest Collection.]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Register, John}}\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n\n\n{{US-painter-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''John Register''' (1939 [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] \u2013 1996 [[Malibu, California|Malibu]], [[California]]) was an American realist painter. \n\n==Background==\nJohn Sherman Register was born in New York City in 1939 to Dorothy Deming Pratt Register and Samuel Croft Register, later graduating from the [[Lawrenceville School]] in New Jersey and the [[University of California]] at Berkeley.  He later studied at the [[California School of Fine Arts]] in San Francisco. After graduating from the University of California, Berkeley, with B.A. in Literature in 1961,John Sherman Register he met his wife Catherine Richards, in a photography class at The Pasadena Art Center where he was studying commercial art. \n\nIn 1964 the two moved to New York, where Register studied design and television at the [[Pratt Institute]] (founded by his great-grandfather).<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> They married on February 6, 1964 and together had three children Peter, Kate and David. \n\nDuring this period Register pursued a career in advertising at McCaffrey and McCall. In 1972, just after his 33rd birthday,<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/>  Register left an important client meeting saying he had a dental appointment and never returning.  He subsequently became a full-time painter, moving is family to California. \n\nRegister photographed the cities they passed through, saying \"I look for offbeat beauty. I don't know what I'm looking for until I find it. There are things so ugly that I can't paint them. Sometimes I get depressed by that city, and by other cities I visit. But I like the patina of things that have been battered by life\".\nJohn Register's vision of isolated streets, empty coffee shops, long shadows, old hotels, and bus stations \"represent a haunting stillness tinged with regret and hope\", wrote Barnaby Conrad in John Register Persistent Observer.\n\nRegister was born with a genetic kidney disease and nearly died numerous times.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/>  He had suffered kidney failure 15 years before his death &mdash; ultimately from cancer from kidney transplant rejection drugs.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> In September 1994, he was told he had four to six weeks to live. He lived instead for 18 months, battling cancer until his death in 1996 at the age of 57, in Malibu, California.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> \n\nAt the time of his death, he was survived by his mother, Dorothy Pratt Barrett of Hillsborough, California; his sister, Barbara Pratt Register of Rolling Hills, California; his brother, Eliot Steven Steven Barrett of St. Helena, California; and his three children, Peter, David and Katie; and one grandson.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/>\n\n==Work==\nHe was honored with a retrospective of his career in 1999.\n\nRegister's work was used, and credited, as the inspiration for the video for \"[[Turn My Head]]\" by the band [[Live (band)|Live]] in 1997.\n\nRegister's work was also featured in the movie [[In Her Shoes (2005 film)|''In Her Shoes'' (2005 film)]].  Director [[Curtis Hanson]] liked the \"loneliness\" that Register's paintings suggested for the feel of the film.\n\n==References==\n* [[Barnaby Conrad III|Conrad, Barnaby III]]. ''John Register: Persistent Observer.'' Duane Press, 1999.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.modernisminc.com/artists/John_REGISTER/ Register at Modernism.]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928175116/http://www.sjmusart.org/content/collection/highlights/paintings/item_info.phtml?itemID=24&typeID=paintings ''Desert Landscape'' at the San Jose Museum of Art.]\n*[http://artregister.com/SeavestIntroductiontoCollection/Catalogue/RegisterConversation.html ''The Conversation'' at the Seavest Collection.]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Register, John}}\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n\n\n{{US-painter-stub}}\n", "name_user": "842U", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Register"}
{"title_page": "168", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Year dab|168|the year of the pre-Julian Roman calendar|168 BC|the New Jersey bus|168 (New Jersey bus)}}\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2020}}\n{{Year nav|168}}\n{{M1 year in topic}}\nYear '''168''' ('''[[Roman numerals|CLXVIII]]''') was a [[leap year starting on Thursday]] (link will display the full calendar) of the [[Julian calendar]]. At the time, it was known as the '''Year of the Consulship of Apronianus and Paullus''' (or, less frequently, '''year 921 ''[[Ab urbe condita]]'''''). The denomination 168 for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the [[Anno Domini]] [[calendar era]] became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.\n\n== Events ==\n<onlyinclude>\n=== By place ===\n==== Roman Empire ====\n* Emperor [[Marcus Aurelius]] and his adopted brother [[Lucius Verus]] leave [[Ancient Rome|Rome]], and establish their headquarters at [[Aquileia]]. \n* The [[Roman army]] crosses the [[Alps]] into [[Pannonia]], and subdues the [[Marcomanni]] at [[Carnuntum]], north of the [[Danube]].\n\n==== Asia ====\n* [[Emperor Ling of Han]] succeeds [[Emperor Huan of Han]] as the emperor of the [[Han dynasty]] in China; first year of the ''Jianning'' era.\n</onlyinclude>\n\n== Births ==\n* [[Cao Ren]], general of the [[Cao Wei]] state in the [[Three Kingdoms]] period (d. [[223]])\n* [[Gu Yong]], official of the [[Eastern Wu]] state in the Three Kingdoms period (d. [[243]])\n\n== Deaths ==\n* [[Pope Anicetus]]\n* [[Dou Wu]], [[Han dynasty]] official and regent\n* [[Emperor Huan of Han]], Han dynasty emperor (b. [[AD 132|132]])<ref>{{cite book |last1=Higham |first1=Charles |title=Encyclopedia of Ancient Asian Civilizations |date=2014 |publisher=Infobase Publishing |isbn=978-1-4381-0996-1 |page=125 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=H1c1UIEVH9gC&pg=PA125&lpg=PA125 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:168}}\n[[Category:168| ]]\n\n[[als:160er#168]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Year dab|168}}\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2020}}\n{{Year nav|168}}\n{{M1 year in topic}}\nYear '''168''' ('''[[Roman numerals|CLXVIII]]''') was a [[leap year starting on Thursday]] (link will display the full calendar) of the [[Julian calendar]]. At the time, it was known as the '''Year of the Consulship of Apronianus and Paullus''' (or, less frequently, '''year 921 ''[[Ab urbe condita]]'''''). The denomination 168 for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the [[Anno Domini]] [[calendar era]] became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.\n\n== Events ==\n<onlyinclude>\n=== By place ===\n==== Roman Empire ====\n* Emperor [[Marcus Aurelius]] and his adopted brother [[Lucius Verus]] leave [[Ancient Rome|Rome]], and establish their headquarters at [[Aquileia]]. \n* The [[Roman army]] crosses the [[Alps]] into [[Pannonia]], and subdues the [[Marcomanni]] at [[Carnuntum]], north of the [[Danube]].\n\n==== Asia ====\n* [[Emperor Ling of Han]] succeeds [[Emperor Huan of Han]] as the emperor of the [[Han dynasty]] in China; first year of the ''Jianning'' era.\n</onlyinclude>\n\n== Births ==\n* [[Cao Ren]], general of the [[Cao Wei]] state in the [[Three Kingdoms]] period (d. [[223]])\n* [[Gu Yong]], official of the [[Eastern Wu]] state in the Three Kingdoms period (d. [[243]])\n\n== Deaths ==\n* [[Pope Anicetus]]\n* [[Dou Wu]], [[Han dynasty]] official and regent\n* [[Emperor Huan of Han]], Han dynasty emperor (b. [[AD 132|132]])<ref>{{cite book |last1=Higham |first1=Charles |title=Encyclopedia of Ancient Asian Civilizations |date=2014 |publisher=Infobase Publishing |isbn=978-1-4381-0996-1 |page=125 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=H1c1UIEVH9gC&pg=PA125&lpg=PA125 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:168}}\n[[Category:168| ]]\n\n[[als:160er#168]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "expand hatnote", "url_page": "